The Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN) said on Tuesday it would grant licenses to more firms willing to operate Cash-In-Transit and Currency Processing (CP) operations across the country. <img class="alignnone  wp-image-1280780" src="https://i1.wp.com/cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/CBN.jpg?resize=556%2C311&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="556" height="311" srcset="https://i1.wp.com/cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/CBN.jpg?w=300&amp;ssl=1 300w, https://i1.wp.com/cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/CBN.jpg?resize=58%2C32&amp;ssl=1 58w, https://i1.wp.com/cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/CBN.jpg?resize=260%2C146&amp;ssl=1 260w, https://i1.wp.com/cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/CBN.jpg?resize=200%2C112&amp;ssl=1 200w" sizes="(max-width: 556px) 100vw, 556px" data-recalc-dims="1" /> The Director of Corporate Communications Department, CBN, Mr. Isaac Okoroafor, disclosed this while speaking on the revised guidelines for the registration of Cash-In-Transit and Currency Processing companies in Nigeria released by the apex bank on Tuesday. Among other things, the guidelines mandate all companies, including deposit money banks, who are desirous of providing currency distribution and/or currency processing services in Nigeria, either for themselves or for other deposit money bank(s) to register with the CBN. The apex bank had in May licensed eight companies as CIT firms and two companies for currency processing.  Vanguard . The Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN) has said that it is ready to license more firms to operate Cash-In-Transit and Currency Processing (CP) operations across the country. October 29, 2019 In "Business" The Governor of the Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN), Mr Godwin Emefiele, says the bank has registered eight companies to carry out Cash-In-Transit (CIT) as part of key policy measures towards promoting effective and efficient currency management in the country. April 30, 2019 In "News" The Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN) has said that Currency Processing Companies (CPCs) must have a minimum capital of N3 billion to obtain get a license to operate nationwide. October 28, 2019 In "Business"